{{short description|A classical, minimally coupled, scalar field postulated to account for the inferred dark matter}}
{{see also|Lambda-CDM model|Galaxy formation}}
[[File:Matter Distribution.JPG|thumb |300px |Pie chart showing the fractions of energy in the universe contributed by different sources. ''Ordinary matter'' is divided into ''luminous matter'' (the stars and luminous gases and 0.005% radiation) and ''nonluminous matter'' (intergalactic gas and about 0.1% neutrinos and 0.04% supermassive black holes). Ordinary matter is uncommon. Modeled after Ostriker and Steinhardt.<ref name=Ostriker>Jeremiah P. Ostriker and Paul Steinhardt [https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0306402 ''New Light on Dark Matter'']</ref> For more information, see [http://map.gsfc.nasa.gov/news/index.html NASA].]] 
In [[astrophysics]] and [[Physical cosmology|cosmology]] '''scalar field dark matter''' is a classical, minimally coupled, scalar field postulated to account for the inferred [[dark matter]].<ref name=Blain>{{cite book |editor=J. Val Blain
|others=Contributors: Reginald T. Cahill, F. Siddhartha Guzman, N. Hiotelis, A.A. Kirillov, V.E. Kuzmichev, V.V. Kuzmichev, A. Miyazaki, Yu. A. Shchekinov, L. Arturo Urena-Lopez, E.I. Vorobyov
|title = Trends in Dark Matter Research |page=40 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=eIHEnqzc-OcC&pg=PA39&dq=%22scalar+field+dark+matter%22#PPA40,M1 |isbn=1-59454-248-1 |date=2005 |publisher=Nova Publishers}}</ref>

==Background==
The universe may be accelerating, fueled perhaps by a cosmological constant or some
other field possessing long range ‘repulsive’ effects. A model must predict the correct form for
the large scale clustering spectrum,<ref name=cluster>Galaxies are not scattered about the universe in a random way, but rather form an intricate network of filaments, sheets, and clusters. How these large-scale structures formed is at the root of many key questions in cosmology.</ref> account for [[cosmic microwave background radiation|cosmic microwave background]] anisotropies on large and intermediate angular scales, and provide agreement with the [[Distance measures (cosmology)|luminosity distance relation]] obtained from observations of high [[redshift]] [[supernova]]e. The modeled evolution of the universe includes a large amount of unknown matter in order to agree with such observations. This matter has two components [[cold dark matter]] and [[dark energy]]. Each contributes to the theory of the origination of galaxies and the expansion of the universe. The universe must have a critical density, a density not explained by  [[baryonic matter]] (ordinary [[matter]]) alone.

==Scalar field==
The dark matter can be modeled as a scalar field using two fitted parameters, mass and [[reflexivity (social theory)|self-interaction]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baldeschi|first=M. R.|last2=Gelmini|first2=G. B.|last3=Ruffini|first3=R.|date=1983-03-10|title=On massive fermions and bosons in galactic halos|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0370269383906883|journal=Physics Letters B|volume=122|issue=3|pages=221–224|doi=10.1016/0370-2693(83)90688-3|bibcode=1983PhLB..122..221B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Membrado|first=M.|last2=Pacheco|first2=A. F.|last3=Sañudo|first3=J.|date=1989-04-01|title=Hartree solutions for the self-Yukawian boson sphere|url=http://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevA.39.4207|journal=Physical Review A|volume=39|issue=8|pages=4207–4211|doi=10.1103/PhysRevA.39.4207|bibcode=1989PhRvA..39.4207M}}</ref> In this picture the dark matter consists of an ultralight particle with a mass of O(10<sup>−22</sup>) eV when there is no self-interaction.<ref>;  T. Matos and L. A. Ureña-López, ''Quintessence and Scalar Dark Matter in the Universe'',  Class. Quantum Grav. '''17''', L75-L81 (2000) [https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0004332 preprint]; ''A Further Analysis of a Cosmological Model of Quintessence and Scalar Dark Matter'', Phys. Rev. D '''63''', 063506 (2001) [https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0006024 preprint]</ref><ref>
V. Sahni and L. Wang, ''A New Cosmological Model of Quintessence and Dark Matter'', Phys. Rev. D '''62''', 103517 (2000) [https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/9910097 preprint]</ref>  If there is a self-interaction a wider mass range is allowed.<ref name=":0" />   The uncertainty in position of a particle is larger than its [[Compton wavelength]], and for some reasonable estimates of particle mass and density of dark matter there is no point talking about the individual particle's position and momentum. The dark matter is more like a wave than a particle, and the [[galactic halo]]s are giant systems of condensed [[Bose–Einstein condensate|bose liquid]], possibly [[Superfluidity|superfluid]]. The dark matter can be described as a Bose–Einstein condensate of the ultralight quanta of the field<ref>S.J. Sin, Phys. Rev., D50, 3650(1994), ''Late-time cosmological phase transition and galactic halo as Bose liquid'' [https://arxiv.org/abs/hep-ph/9205208 preprint],</ref> and as boson stars.<ref name=":0">J. Lee and I. Koh Phys. Rev. D 53,2236 (1996),''Galactic Halos As Boson Stars''
[https://arxiv.org/abs/hep-ph/9507385 preprint]</ref> The enormous Compton wavelength of these particles prevents structure formation on small subgalactic scales, which is a major problem in traditional cold dark matter models. The collapse of initial overdensities is studied in Refs.<ref>M. Alcubierre, F. S. Guzmán, T. Matos, D. Núñez, L. A. Ureña-López and P. Wiederhold, ''Galactic Collapse of Scalar Field Dark Matter'', Class. Quantum Grav. '''19''', 5017 (2002) [https://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0110102 preprint]; F. S. Guzmán and L. A. Ureña-López, ''Evolution of the Schrödinger--Newton system for a self--gravitating scalar field'', Phys. Rev. D '''69''', 124033 (2004) [https://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0404014 preprint]; ''Gravitational cooling of self-gravitating Bose-Condensates'', ApJ. '''645''', 814 (2006) [https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0603613 preprint]; A. Bernal and F. S. Guzmán, ''Scalar Field Dark Matter: non-spherical collapse and late time behavior'', Phys. Rev. D '''74''', 063504 (2006) [https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0608523 preprint].</ref>

This dark matter model is also known as BEC dark matter or wave dark matter.  [[Fuzzy cold dark matter|Fuzzy dark matter]] and ultra-light axion are  examples of scalar field dark matter.

